  "prompt": "What causes a sonic boom?",
  "response": "A sonic boom is caused when an object travels through the air at a speed faster than the speed of sound, creating shock waves. This phenomenon occurs because the object compresses the air in front of it, causing pressure waves to build up and merge into a single shock wave. When this shock wave passes by an observer, it is heard as a loud, explosive noise known as a sonic boom.\n\nThe speed at which this occurs is referred to as the speed of sound, or Mach 1, and varies depending on factors like air temperature and altitude. Typically, the speed of sound at sea level is about 343 meters per second (1,235 kilometers per hour or 767 miles per hour). When an aircraft or other object exceeds this speed, it breaks the sound barrier, leading to the creation of a sonic boom.",
